% Theoretical Motivation
\citet[1]{Levi:1989lq} has famously explained that ``the history of state revenue production is the history of the evolution of the state.'' However, even when we have gained considerable knowledge of fiscal expansion in the European cases, the study of the public finances within a context of state consolidation in the developing world is lacking, especially in the presence of ``new leading sectors.''\footnote{\citet[2]{Schneider:2012rr}.} In fact, while there are a number of theories about state-capacity in Latin America, domestic explanations centered on the role of the economic structural transformation and taxation have been overlooked.\footnote{A few exceptions are \citet[7-8]{Gallo:1991kx}, \citet{Beramendi2016} and \citet[8]{Saylor:2014aa} who consider elite conflicts to study state-making and fiscal development in the developing world. \citet{Dargent2017} focus on a ```challenger-based' causal mechanism'' of state formation in Peru, however they concentrate their efforts on the role of exogenous economic shocks.} Besides this theoretical gap, there is also an empirical deficit. As \citet[586]{Soifer2012} points out, most ``scholarship on state capacity [...] lack[s] a satisfying conceptualization and measurement scheme for this concept.'' Moreover, while most state formation theories are situated during precolonial,\footnote{\citet{Mahoney:2010aa}.} early,\footnote{See \citet[]{Kurtz:2013aa} and \citet[]{Soifer2015a}.} or late\footnote{\citet{Bahamonde:2017ab}.} independent Latin America, we lack a measurement that corresponds \emph{temporally} to the theories we have. In other words, most explanations of state-making are \emph{historical} in nature. Yet, in practice, available measurements capture \emph{contemporary} levels of \emph{stateness}. 





