\section{Sectoral Conflict, State Capacity, and the Case of the Income Tax in Chile \label{argument}}


% agr were important
The landed Latin American elites were an economic hegemonic group protected by norms and institutions that originated during colonial times.\footnote{\citet[13]{Keller1931}.} Moreover, the post-colonial institutional and economic orders were designed to give an unfair advantage to the agricultural sector. \citet[99]{Mamalakis1971} is well-known for describing how an agriculture-government coalition was formed in Chile beginning with the colonial period. Several historians also point out that ``[i]n those areas where the government did interfere in the countryside, the effect was to strengthen the position of the landowning class.''\footnote{\citet[118]{Bauer:2008kx}.} In fact, the little public infrastructure that existed mostly benefited the agricultural sector.\footnote{\citet{Rippy:1971rz,Marichal:1989bh,Zeitlin:1984aa,Bauer:2008kx}.} By extension, the landowning class controlled most of the politics too.\footnote{\citet[45-46]{Wright1975}, \citet[13]{Zeitlin:1984aa}, \citet[45]{Bauer:2008kx}, \citet[1748]{Baland2008}, \citet[56]{Best1976}, \citet{Rippy:1971rz} and \citet{Marichal:1989bh}.} For instance, \citet[106]{Collier:2002db} explain that the Chilean ``national government was dominated by the central part of the country, with owners of large agricultural holdings playing a predominant role.''\footnote{Similarly, \citet[15]{McBride:1971fv} explains that ``Chile's people live on the soil. Her life is agricultural to the core. \emph{Her government has always been of farm owners. Her Congress is made up chiefly of rich landlords}. Social life is dominated by families whose proudest possession is the ancestral estate.'' Emphases are mine.} 

% but then industrialists emerged
However, when the structural transformation took place,\footnote{Defined as the ``secular decline of agriculture and substantial expansion of manufacturing'' (\citet[567]{Johnston1961}). } this process imposed tight constraints on the way politics was run by the incumbent landowning class. Given the foundational advantage of the landed elites, the secular emergence of the industrial sector translated into lower levels of inter-sectoral inequality, generating political, economic, and military threats to the landed elites.\footnote{As \citet{Boix:2015aa} explains, lower levels of inter-elite economic inequality are tied to similar degrees of military capabilities. Under these circumstances, war is most likely to exhaust all existent assets without producing positive outcomes for either sector (Richard Salvucci in \citet[48]{Uribe-Uran:2001aa}) leading to heavier pressures to reach agreements instead of engaging in armed conflicts. In Chile, while initially both ``antagonistic elites'' (\citet[37-38]{Keller1931}) confronted each other in two bloody civil wars between a ``large landed property [elite against a] productive capital[ist] [elite]'' (\citet[23]{Zeitlin:1984aa}), due to low levels of inequality, war was not sustainable over time. For instance, while \emph{Balmacedistas} managed to secure the support of the army, \emph{congresistas} (the anti-Balmaceda group) gathered support from the navy. Similarly, in the subsequent years of the civil war, there were a number of \emph{aborted} coups, in 1907, 1912, 1915, and 1919 (in \citet[109]{Collier:2002db}), suggesting an equilibrium where no elite was the leading elite.} For instance, before the civil war, \emph{salitreras} (nitrate towns) in northern Chile were so prominent that they were considered ``a state within the state.''\footnote{\citet[500]{Barros:1970aa}. My translation.} Industrial bosses had to approve decisions on whether public employees could be fired, whether public works could be developed, and on whether politicians could give public speeches. \emph{Salitrera} industries also coined their own currency, and had their own particular local laws.




%The higher the threats, the more likely the inter-sectoral compromises (yellow box in \autoref{causal:mechanism:fig}). One particular compromise is identified---the implementation of the income tax---and special attention is paid to how this institution expanded state-capacities over time.  Elite incorporation was possible, contingent on outsiders' capacity for challenging the institutional order that permitted hegemonic groups to rule without opposition. 



% from conflict to compromise: income tax
The preferences over fiscal policy of the expanding industrial sector clashed with the ones of the agricultural class. On the one hand, land fixity increased the risk premium of the landed elite's main asset,\footnote{\citet[512]{Robinson2006a}.} so they systematically resisted taxation. However, as capital could be reinvested in nontaxable sectors,\footnote{\citet[]{Hirschman:1970bl}. See Ronald Rogowski in \citet[ch. 4]{Drake:1998pi}. However, see \citet[15]{Bates1985}.} industrialists' preferences toward taxation were more elastic. Consequently, the emergence of a strong industrial class led to heavier pressures for the implementation of the income tax law. As industrialists depended more on infrastructure implemented at the local level---such as roads, railroads, and bridges---the industrial classes in Latin America ``[\emph{preferred}] to shoulder a higher tax burden through progressive direct taxation.''\footnote{\citet[18]{Beramendi2016}.} In fact, in 1924 Chilean industrial elites accepted to be income taxed by agriculturalist incumbents \emph{in exchange} for having more state services and being included in state politics. As others have explained, the non-agricultural sector ``accepted taxation, while demanding state services and expecting to influence how tax revenues were spent [...] Consultation and cooperation were relatively institutionalised between the two sides.''\footnote{Carmenza Gallo, in \citet[165]{Brautigam2008}. Emphases are mine.} Since both elites agreed on implementing the income tax, compliance was high. Institutionalist economists find that optimal institutional choices result from political settings where all involved actors ``had a voice in the choice of institutions,''\footnote{\citet[566]{Aghion2004}.} essentially contributing to an equilibrium of quasi-voluntary compliance.\footnote{\citet{Levi:1989lq}.} 




% income tax --> positive externalities of income taxation (0)
The tax was not only important because of the new revenue it collected. In line with the fiscal sociology paradigm, the tax was also important for state consolidation. \citet[99]{Musgrave1992} argues that since taxation (especially on incomes) requires such a high degree of state penetration, public finances offer also a theory of state-building. Indirect taxes are easier to levy, and, hence, this kind of revenue is generally considered ``unearned income''\footnote{\citet[304]{Moore2004a}.} or ``easy-to-collect source of revenues.''\footnote{\citet[10]{Coatsworth2002}.} Given the relatively lower costs states have to incur to collect them, indirect taxes have a very low impact on state-building.\footnote{\citet[14]{Moore2004}.} For example, \citet[46]{Krasner:1985lq} explains that ``tariffs and export taxes are easier to obtain than direct taxes, which require high levels of bureaucratic skill and voluntary compliance.'' In fact, when early Latin American states depended heavily on trade taxes, the state apparatus tended to be less developed.\footnote{\citet[177]{Campbell1993}.} Since customs administrations have always been concentrated in a few critical locations, especially ports, tariffs and customs duties often times did not require an elaborate fiscal structure.\footnote{\citet[132]{Bertola2012}.} 


% income tax --> positive externalities of income taxation (1)
The very implementation of the income tax fostered state-consolidation via spillovers,\footnote{\citet[98]{Musgrave1992} and \citet[298]{Moore2004a} explain that transforming private incomes into public property fostered state expansion.} or \emph{technical complementarities}, which are situations in which ``an increase in the output of [a] commodity [...] lowers the marginal costs of producing [other] commodity.''\footnote{\citet[67]{Hirschman:1958aa}.} The literature points out that the \emph{introduction} of the income tax has been indeed associated with state expansion. For instance, Kaldor explains that the revenue service is the ``point of entry.'' Once this institution is secured, securing the rest is marginally easier.\footnote{In \citet[15]{Brautigam2008}.} In turn, \citet{Besley2013a} explain that \emph{implementing} the income tax law is ``associated with investments in public administrative structures that support tax collection'' in a number of countries, including Chile, while \citet[3]{Dincecco2015a} find ``a positive and significant relationship between the introduction of the income tax and (1) per capita total expenditures, (2) per capita education expenditures, and (3) per capita health expenditures.'' 

In Chile, bureaucrats that were sent to collect and administer taxes eventually learned to solve land disputes and dispense justice, among other state tasks. For instance, it was necessary to send official emissaries to check on accounting books of the refinery in the north, the winery in the central valley, and the \emph{hacienda} in the south. Eventually, these delegations became more complex, increasing the density of state presence in the territory.\footnote{For the European context, \citet{Strayer:2005uq} explains how official state delegations traveled the territory dispensing judicial decisions, thereby fostering state centralization.} Others have found that literacy levels rose in 1907 from 40\% to 66\% in 1925,\footnote{Engerman, Sokoloff and Mariscal, in \citet[Ch. 5]{Engerman:2011aa}.} the share of national revenue accounted for by income taxes after implementing the income tax in 1924, rose from 6\% in 1920 to 23.7\% in 1940,\footnote{Engerman, Sokoloff and Zolt, in \citet[178]{Engerman:2011aa}. Humud (1969, p. 154) documents that the income tax was widely enforced, generating considerable resources for the Chilean treasury (in \citet[451-452]{Bowman1982}).} and that the dependence on custom taxes decreased from 70.2\% to 41.1\% during those same years.\footnote{Engerman, Sokoloff and Zolt, in \citet[Ch. 6]{Engerman:2011aa}.} These developments suggest that policies that expanded the reach of the state, particularly schooling and taxation, increased considerably \emph{after} implementing the income tax.

\emph{Did the implementation of the income tax in Chile foster state development over time?} The next section motivates the measurement approach pursued in this paper. The following section leverages a number of quantitative models that show that (1) income taxation in Chile fostered state development over time, (2) implementing the income tax in Latin America was attributed to the emergence of the industrial sector, not overall economic growth, (3) in Chile, both sectors were in permanent conflict, precluding cross-sectoral investments.

\section{From Earthquake Death Tolls to State Capacities\label{measurement}}

% different measures
More than being blessed, the literature is in fact cursed due to an over-abundance of poor indicators of state consolidation.\footnote{\citet[589]{Soifer2012}.} In fact, its abundance ``points to the poor state of empirical measures of the quality of states.''\footnote{\citet[347]{Fukuyama2013}.} %The literature points to two major concerns. First, ``most fragility indices barely satisfy scientific standards''\footnote{\citet[35]{Mata2009}. They point out particularly to the fact that data are usually poor.} and, second, most indices are conflated with analytical and conceptual problems.\footnote{See also \citet[1292]{Ferreira2017}.} 


One notable example is protection of the rule of law, which is commonly used as proxy for state capacities.\footnote{See for one example \citet[1237]{Besley2009}.} As \citet[543]{Kurtz2007} explain, this strategy is severely confounded ``with policy preferences over the structure of private property rights.'' On the one hand, this is problematic since the sources of this data are usually elite interviews.\footnote{\citet[349]{Fukuyama2013}.} To ``the extent that public bureaucracies \emph{are} effective in imposing taxes or regulatory demands [...] they are likely to be judged `burdensome' and `growth-inhibiting' by many businesspersons,''\footnote{\citet[542]{Kurtz2007}.} thereby introducing systematic measurement error.\footnote{See also \citet[618]{Kurtz2012}.} On the other hand, the problem is conceptual. As \citet[247]{Soifer2008a} puts it, there is a widely spread ``problem of misalignment between dimension and indicator.'' \citet[619]{Kurtz2012} recommend ``explicitly avoid[ing] an emphasis on outputs that are at the center of political or policy debates, such as property rights.'' For example, the U.S.S.R. had a strong state, however it did \emph{not} protect property rights. 

Another iconic example of this misalignment problem is the use of fiscal extraction as a proxy of state capacity. \citet[3]{Johnson2017} explain that ``[t]ax revenue per capita is a commonly used metric of fiscal capacity,''  which in turn speaks to levels of state-capacity. In fact, \citet[172]{Thies2015} conceptualizes ``fiscal capacity [...] in terms of tax revenue extracted from society.''\footnote{Other examples are \citet[224]{Besley2013a} and \citet{Besley2014}.} Not only tax shares reflect policy preferences too,\footnote{\citet[9]{Soifer2013a}.} but also, as \citet[353]{Fukuyama2013} explains it, there ``is a difference between extractive \emph{potential} and \emph{actual} extraction rates.''\footnote{Emphases are mine.} For instance, since American institutions were deliberately designed to limit the exercise of state power, the U.S. taxes very little.\footnote{\citet[6]{Fukuyama:2004nr}.} However, it is not reasonable to say that the U.S. has a ``weak state.'' Moreover, in late imperial China, ``high taxes on peasants [...] were the result of rulers' \emph{lack} of power. Chinese rulers consistently attempted to limit officials' excessive extractions from the masses, but were unable to do so.''\footnote{\citet[301]{Kiser1992}. Emphasis is mine.} 

Finally, others have proxied state-capacity with economic growth, which is also problematic.\footnote{\citet{Fearon2003} and \citet{Besley:2011aa}, and \citet[4, 6-7]{Mahoney:2010aa}.} As \citet{Dargent2017} explain, state-capacity and economic growth are causally distinct mechanisms. For instance, boom-led economic growth has left net state capacity  low in Peru.



% temporal
This paper identifies an additional limitation. Beyond conceptual and analytical problems, most available measurements are unable to capture temporal sources of variation of state capacity. Since most explanations of state-making have a strong historical component, the lack of an indicator able to \emph{travel in time} represents a huge deficit in the literature. Just to name a few examples, \citet[585]{Soifer2012} ``builds a new measure of state capacity for [...] \emph{contemporary} Latin America [combining] multiple dimensions (extraction, security, and the administration of basic services).''\footnote{Emphasis is mine.} \citet[618-619]{Kurtz2012} designed some list-experiments to study bureaucrat's opinions, \citet{Dargent2017} ``analyses the evolution of state capacity in Peru during the \emph{recent} commodity boom,''\footnote{Emphasis is mine.} while \citet{Luna2014,Luna2017} employ a survey-based design to measure \emph{contemporary} subnational state capacities. While these measurements do overcome the conceptual and analytical problems mentioned above, they do not help us in studying state capacities in a historical setup. 


Economic historians offer other alternatives. Some examples are levels of investments in public goods,\footnote{\citet{Enriquez2017}.} such as infrastructure, roads,\footnote{\citet{Mann1984a,Mann2008a,Acemoglu2005a,Saylor2012,Thies2009,Besley2010}.} electrification (measured as light intensity per pixel),\footnote{\citet{Huntington2014}.} and railroads.\footnote{\citet[302]{Saylor2012} and \citet{Coatsworth1974a}.} However, many of these measurements are debatable. For instance, \citet[593]{Soifer2012} explains that ``railroads were often constructed by private actors.''\footnote{Footnote \#11.} The same problem applies to other types of infrastructure. There are others more appropriate strategies, such as the opening of postal offices,\footnote{\citet{Robinson2016}.} the administration of national censuses,\footnote{\citet{Lee2017}, \citet{Soifer2013a}, \citet{Centeno:2002qf} and \citet{Hanson2013,Hanson2015}. Another variation of this technique is ``age heaping.''} and vaccination.\footnote{\citet{Soifer2012}.} While these measurements do capture historical variations of state capacities, some other problems arise. Censuses, for example, provide a \emph{non-continuous temporal measurement} of state capacities. For instance, censuses are applied in Chile every ten years. Having just a few snapshots of state-capacity should compromise any statistical analysis. In turn, vaccines are usually targeted at primary and high school students. In practice, vaccines are administered by the schools themselves, both public and private. Private schools might be more efficient in doing so, inflating the \emph{average} level of state-capacity. 


% my measurement
To solve some of these limitations, the paper proposes earthquake death tolls as an alternative to measure state capacities over time. Unlike censuses---\emph{unfortunately}--- earthquakes happen in Chile very often. While ``[e]arthquakes alone claim thousands of lives a year,''\footnote{\citet[1908]{Anbarci2005}.} they are not well studied in the discipline.\footnote{\citet[719]{Brancati2007} explains that ``[d]isasters are not as well studied [...] in the field of political science.''} Building on \citet[113]{Mann1984a}, the proposed measurement intends to capture the state's \emph{infrastructural} power.\footnote{He defines infrastructural power as  ``the capacity of the state [to] actually [...] penetrate civil society, and to implement logistically political decisions throughout the realm.''} ``Natural hazards can be seen as a function of a specific natural process and human [...] activity.''\footnote{\citet[627]{Raschky2008}.} Given that earthquakes happen at random and are exogenous to the affected locality,\footnote{\citet[728]{Brancati2007} explains that ``earthquakes constitute a natural experiment.'' \citet[27]{Gignoux2016} also point out ``that the occurrence of earthquakes can be viewed as random [allowing the analyses of] these events as a set of repeated social experiments.'' \citet[32, unpublished]{Caruso2017}, for instance, ``[exploits] the exogenous variation in the location and timing of natural disasters.''} the only part that is left unexplained is the systematic human component, which is what the measurement captures. Earthquakes are orthogonal to levels of state capacity and economic development.\footnote{\citet[271]{Kahn2005} and \citet{Brancati2007}.} Thus, keeping earthquake magnitudes constant at their means, (population-weighted) death counts should be attributed to the (\emph{in})capacity of the states to invest in preparedness and earthquake-mitigation institutions.\footnote{To make sure, while ``earthquakes may not be preventable, it is possible to prevent the disasters they cause'' (\citet[209]{Escaleras2007}). Similarly, \citet[1911]{Anbarci2005} explain that ``the potentially devastating effects of major earthquakes are, if not preventable, at least subject to significant mitigation.'' For a similar approach, see \citet[130]{Noji:1996aa}.} I focus on earthquakes and not on other natural disasters, such as ``extreme temperature events, floods, landslides, and windstorms,''\footnote{\citet[280]{Kahn2005}.} because earthquakes cannot be foreseen and, as such, they put to test the states' capacity for having their preventive institutions \emph{already} in place and in good shape.\footnote{In fact, \citet[716]{Brancati2007} explains that ``[e]arthquakes may provoke conflict more than any other type of natural disaster because they have rapid onsets [and] are not predictable.'' Emphasis is mine.} State capacity consist of sustained proactive efforts of enforcing institutions in the territory, and, hence, short-term reactive actions should not be considered state-\emph{making}. 



% preparedeness // construction
Under reasonable assumptions, the capacity of deploying inspectors to enforce quake-sensitive zoning and building codes should be a reflection of the overall levels of state capacity. Since ``[e]arthquake-resistant construction depends on responsible governance,''\footnote{\citet[153]{Ambraseys2011}. Similarly, \citet[628]{Raschky2008} argue that ``the effects of natural hazards [do] not solely depend on a region's topographic or climatic exposure to natural processes [...] but [on] the region's \emph{institutional} vulnerability.'' Emphasis is mine.} state capacity act as a scope condition undermining (facilitating) the implementation of these norms. For example, \citet[169]{Bilham2013} explains that ``although engineering codes may \emph{exist}[,] mechanisms to \emph{implement} these codes are largely unavailable''\footnote{Emphases are mine.} in low-capacity states. For example, \citet[1910]{Anbarci2005} explain that ``while Iran has building codes [...] comparable to those existing in the United States, they tend to be enforced only in the country's larger cities,'' not in the countryside.

% marco legal
Only high-capacity states overcome their own limitations, not only implementing but also enforcing quake-sensitive regulations. The Chilean government started its efforts to ameliorate the impact of earthquakes after the great quake of 1928 in Talca. A first effort happened in 1929, when \href{http://www.leychile.cl/Navegar?idNorma=149306}{\emph{Ley} number 4563} was implemented. The law was among the first attempts to prohibit ``construction, reconstruction or any other repairing or transformations [...] without a permit from the authorities.'' Importantly, the law required that all blueprints had to be signed off by an expert before the construction started. By 1930, \href{https://www.leychile.cl/Navegar?idNorma=1038437&idParte=0&idVersion=}{\emph{Decreto} number 4882} was adopted, but this time the rule made a number of technical prescriptions,\footnote{See especially article 151.} determining what kinds of construction materials ought to be used, among other requirements. Critically, while the central government had retained the control of the supervision of the code since the promulgation of the \emph{ley}, the \emph{decreto} explicitly created the role of the \emph{inspector} to supervise, enforce, and monitor these measures at the local level. Furthermore, \emph{art\'iculo} 414 of the Chilean \emph{Decreto} 4882 granted inspectors ``free access to the building'' at any time during the construction process. The proposed measurement captures whether these good intentions achieved lower death tolls.


% advantages // it's objective and subnational
The proposed measurement has a number of advantages. Unlike non-experimental survey-based or purely policy-based measures, earthquake death tolls are an \emph{objective} measurement of earthquake preparedness, an activity that \emph{any} state \emph{must} perform.\footnote{\citet[422]{Carlin2014a} explain that ``a basket of `minimal' state functions [typically includes] primary education, public health, rule of law, public finance management, and disaster relief.''} However, the measurement has a number of drawbacks. Obviously, the country needs to have earthquakes, possibly limiting the number of potential cases. However, most earthquakes occur at the various borders of the Pacific, Latin American, African, Arabic, Indian and Eurasian plates,\footnote{\citet[1534]{Keefer2011}.} allowing a number of potential cross-country comparisons.\footnote{\citet[1534]{Keefer2011}. From a population size perspective, this measurement is also convenient. A ``quarter of the world's population inhabits [...] the northern edge of the Arabian and Indian Plates that are colliding with the southern margin of the Eurasian Plate'' (\citet[618]{Bilham2013a}).} Thus, like other measurements available, this is a context-specific strategy. For instance, \citet[593]{Soifer2012} and \citet[252]{Slater2008} propose a measurement based on whether states are able to enforce voter registration ``where voting is mandatory,'' or conduct ``state registration of marginal populations,'' respectively, limiting the study of state-capacity to democratic countries only.


Moving forward, there are countries, like India or the United States, where earthquakes happen in certain regions only. Presumably, mitigation policies in these places would need to be targeted to specific areas, possibly undermining the assumption that these kinds of policies should penetrate the entire territory.\footnote{\citet[164]{Dunbar2003} explains that the Indian state implements targeted policies (that might not necessarily correspond to the administrative areas) based on isoseismal maps that define different zones of seismic hazard.} Another potential concern is that the ability of counting the death-toll might be a function of state capacities itself.\footnote{I thank Paul Poast for this comment.} However, in most cases, civic organizations, the Catholic Church, and, particularly, the press (national and local) have been the main entities who (willingly or not) have carried out the task of enumerating the deaths. Another potential issue is the measurement of the magnitudes. Before the instrumental period, magnitudes were obtained in an estimative way, and, while there are methods to approximate historically-felt magnitudes to instrumental-like intensities,\footnote{\citet{Szeliga2010}.} this strategy unfortunately adds more than one layer of complexity. All in all, this measurement offers a rough approximation of levels of state capacities over time.




\section{Empirical Section\label{models}}


\subsection{Spillover Effects of Income Taxation on State Capacity}

% explain dataset: 
I constructed a novel hand-collected longitudinal dataset using the \emph{Significant Earthquake Database} compiled by the National Centers for Environmental Information (NOAA) as a starting point.\footnote{\citet[]{noaa2015}.} The dataset ``contains information on destructive earthquakes from 2150 B.C. to the present,'' and records the number of deaths,\footnote{Tsunami casualties were excluded.} the magnitude, date, latitude, and longitude of every quake, among other variables. Using archival census data from 1907 to 2012,\footnote{Particularly, censuses of 1907, 1920, 1930, 1940, 1952, 1960, 1970, 1982, 1992, 2002 and 2012. Some of them were kept at the \emph{Biblioteca Nacional} and others at the \emph{National Statistic Institute} historical library.} the NOAA dataset was complemented with local population at the municipal level where the quake hit. Local population was used to weight the death toll.\footnote{Around 90\% of the times it was possible to recover the actual local population. For the rest, the population of the most concentrated area nearby was recovered. Consequently, population is used as a control, not to directly weight the dependent variable.} Using archival census data as well, the main economic activity of the affected municipality was coded,\footnote{This variable was constructed by coding press and official sources (mainly censuses) of the main economic sector at the local level. \text{$\Sexpr{levels(factor(datsc$Sector))[1]}$} (n=$\Sexpr{as.character(table(factor(datsc$Sector))[1])}$), \text{$\Sexpr{levels(factor(datsc$Sector))[2]}$} (n=$\Sexpr{as.character(table(factor(datsc$Sector))[2])}$), \text{$\Sexpr{levels(factor(datsc$Sector))[3]}$} (n=$\Sexpr{as.character(table(factor(datsc$Sector))[3])}$). This corresponds to the full sample. } in addition to whether the municipality was urban or rural.\footnote{Urban=$\Sexpr{table(datsc$Urban[datsc$Urban==1])}$, rural=$\Sexpr{table(datsc$Urban[datsc$Urban==0])}$. If more than 50\% of the population lived in an urban setting, I assigned a 1 to that municipality, 0 otherwise. Urban concentrations are most likely to have vertical constructions rather than one-story buildings, increasing the potential number of casualties. Consequently, it is important to control for this source of variation. I thank Daniel Kelemen for this suggestion.} The death tolls and magnitudes proportionated by the NOAA dataset were contrasted case by case with historical press archival information.\footnote{\emph{El Mercurio} and \emph{La Naci\'on} newspapers, both kept at the \emph{Archivo Nacional} of the \emph{Biblioteca Nacional de Chile}.} Magnitudes, in particular, were also compared with the \href{http://www.isc.ac.uk/iscbulletin/search/bulletin/}{International Seismological Centre}. 

% case justification
\autoref{fig:earthquake:ts:plot:chile} plots the over time earthquakes and magnitudes, while \autoref{fig:earthquake:map:plot:chile} plots the geographical distribution and magnitudes of the quakes, as well as the dominant productive sector.\footnote{For illustrative purposes, both plots consider the full sample starting in $\Sexpr{min(dat.chile$year)}$ and ending in $\Sexpr{max(dat.chile$year)}$.} Both figures suggest that Chile is a good case to study infrastructural state-capacity using the earthquake framework, since it has considerable variance regarding quake magnitudes, locations and sectoral variation. The northern part of Chile has historically been an industrial region, while the southern part of Chile has traditionally been an agricultural region. Relatedly, both regions vary according to their climate. Furthermore, the distance from Santiago, which is located near latitude 33$^{\circ}$, might impose some degree of difficulty for the central government to reach the farthest northern/southern parts of the territory.\footnote{\citet[418]{Foa2016}.} There is also variance considering longitude. Closeness to the Andean mountains (around longitude 70$^{\circ}$) determines the ruggedness of the terrain, presumably making it harder for the state to penetrate these areas.\footnote{\citet[729]{Brancati2007} explains that ``[e]arthquakes often occur in mountainous areas.''} All things considered, earthquakes have affected the territory from coast to mountain,\footnote{Since ``most of the damage in major earthquakes occurs within 30 km of the epicenter,'' (\citet[172]{Dunbar2003}) earthquakes that did not happen on land were not dropped. While the epicentre might have been a few miles away from the shore, the consequences certainly reached the land.} and both north and south, solving potential concerns about geographical sectoral self-selection.


