% Poisson model // main IVs
The unit of analysis is the earthquake.\footnote{\citet[273]{Kahn2005} also considers that ``the unit of analysis is [the] disaster.''} As an event, each earthquake has associated to it a death toll, a location, a magnitude, a local population, and an urban/rural setting. Specifically, following the statistical convention, a Bayesian Poisson regression was employed to test the effect of implementing the income tax law on death-tolls over time.\footnote{\citet[1907]{Anbarci2005} use ``a Negative Binomial estimation strategy with both random and fixed estimators'' to estimate death-tolls, \citet[276]{Kahn2005} estimates a Zero Inflated Negative Binomial model, \citet[729]{Brancati2007} uses ``a negative binomial model with robust standard errors clustered by country,'' and \citet{Escaleras2007} use ``a Negative Binomial.'' Yet, no study tests for over dispersion. No evidence of over dispersion is found in the analyzed dataset.} The main quantity of interest is a binary variable (i.e. \emph{Income Tax}) that denotes whether the income tax is implemented or not. The model considers year fixed-effects to account for time-varying confounding factors and for unmeasured sources of variation.\footnote{More formally, \autoref{model:2} was fitted:
\begin{equation} \label{model:2}
\begin{split}
\text{Deaths} \;\sim\; & \text{Poisson}(\lambda_{i})\\
log(\lambda_{i})  = 
&\;\mu + 
\beta_{1}\text{Income Tax}_{i} + 
\beta_{2}\text{Magnitude}^2_{i} +
\beta_{3}\text{Latitude}_{i} + 
\beta_{4}\text{Longitude}_{i} + \\
& \beta_{5}\text{Population}_{i} +
\beta_{6}\text{Urban}_{i} + 
\beta_{7}\text{Year}_{i}
\end{split}
\end{equation}


\href{https://data.noaa.gov/dataset/earthquake-damage-general}{According to the NOAA}, an ``increase of one in magnitude represents a tenfold increase in the recorded wave amplitude.'' To account for non-linear effects, \autoref{model:2} considers the square term of magnitude. Parameters $\beta_{k}$ have noninformative normally distributed priors. Precisions $\tau_{p}$ have noninformative Gamma priors. See \autoref{indexes:2} for technical details. \citet[729]{Brancati2007} also includes in his analyses ``year-fixed effects to control for trends over time.''} For instance, fiscal development is also a function of country-specific prior state-capacities. Additionally, technological changes (advances in construction, for example) should diminish death-tolls.\footnote{I thank Hillel Soifer for this suggestion.} Fixed-effects should be able to account for these and other unmeasured yearly factors. In addition, local population also serves as a rough proxy for local economic development,\footnote{\citet{Sokoloff:2000ug}.} which might impact negatively casualties. Latitude was included to control for the proximity to the Andean mountains, aiming to control for a built-in tectonic earthquake predisposition. Longitude seeks to control for climate and other unmeasured conditions that make agricultural development more difficult. In turn, both measurements serve as good proxies of terrain ruggedness and the difficulties the state faces in reaching these areas.\footnote{Undoubtedly, there are many more factors that might increase death tolls. \citet[154]{Ambraseys2011}, for example, explain that the ``number of fatalities depends on whether an earthquake happens at night or during the day, in the winter or in the summer, in a mountainous region or in a valley, after strong and protracted fore-shocks and with or without warning.'' While the model has some of these factors accounted for, complete hourly data is lacking. However, \citet[1309]{Lomnitz1970} explains that ``some of the larger Chilean earthquakes which have caused deaths'' between the 1900's and the 1960's have been afternoon quakes. Other factors such as ``the speed of tectonic movements [and] the degree to which the lower plate bends the upper plate'' and the focal depth (\citet[1534]{Keefer2011}) could not be included due to the lack of complete data over time.} 


Fiscal sociologists, mostly focusing on the continental cases, have for a long time claimed that the capacity of taxing individuals' incomes fosters overall state-capacities. Unfortunately, there have not been attempts to study this relationship for the Latin American cases. The results presented in \autoref{income:tax:model:regression:table:run} find support for this claim. Particularly, implementing the income tax \emph{decreases} the death-toll by an estimated over time average of $\Sexpr{abs(round(reg.results.table.tax$Mean[rownames(reg.results.table.tax) == 'Income Tax'],0))}$. \autoref{fig:income:tax:model:plot:run} shows that death-tolls (state capacities) systematically \emph{decrease} (increase) over time once the income tax law is implemented. Before the income tax law was implemented, death-tolls were relatively stable, averaging approximately $\Sexpr{death.toll.before.tax}$  casualties per earthquake. However, once the income tax law was implemented, the death-toll decreased to $\Sexpr{death.toll.after.tax}$. Moreover, the figure shows that the trajectory of casualties goes from $\Sexpr{round(income.tax.adoption.plot$mean[income.tax.adoption.plot$year == min(income.tax.adoption.plot$year)], 0)}$ in $\Sexpr{min(income.tax.adoption.plot$year)}$ to $\Sexpr{round(income.tax.adoption.plot$mean[income.tax.adoption.plot$year == max(income.tax.adoption.plot$year)], 0)}$ in $\Sexpr{max(income.tax.adoption.plot$year)}$. The fixed-effects estimation makes these results robust to considerations of geography and economic development.


