% MODELS
Econometrically, this section is concerned about the \emph{timing} of implementing the income tax law in nine Latin American polities, and particularly, about the individual contribution of both the agricultural and industrial sectors. \autoref{results:table:cox} shows 3 models.\footnote{Tables were produced using the  \texttt{texreg} package (\citet[]{Leifeld:2013qr}). All Cox models were computed using the \texttt{survival R}  package (\citet{Therneau:2015zr}). The GEE logistic regression was computed using the \texttt{geepack} package (\citet[]{Hojsgaard:2016}). The simulations were performed using the \texttt{simPH R} package (\citet{Gandrud2015}).} Following \citet{Aidt2009a}, Model 1 computes the lagged conditional hazard ratio of a country which has not yet adopted the income tax adopts it in a given year, as a function of industrial and agricultural outputs.\footnote{Since the idea is to capture the \emph{sectoral contribution} of the implementation of the income tax law, these variables were not combined. Following \citet[49]{Box-Steffensmeier2004}, the next equation was fitted: 
\begin{equation}\label{cox:eq}
h_{i}(t) = exp(\beta_{1}\text{Industrial Growth}_{i,t} + \beta_{2}\text{Agricultural Growth}_{i,t} + \beta_{3}\text{Total Population}_{i,t})h_{0}(t)
\end{equation}
for all countries $i$ and years $t$.} Countries drop out of the sample when they adopt the income tax. Model 2 shows the estimated coefficients of a generalized estimating equation (GEE).\footnote{Following \citet[331]{Zorn2006}, the next equation was fitted:
\begin{equation}\label{gee:eq}
\pi_{i,t}=\Phi(\beta_{1}\text{log(Industrial Growth)}_{i,t}+\beta_{2}\text{log(Agricultural Growth)}_{i,t}+\beta_{3}\text{log(Total Population)}_{i,t})
\end{equation}
where $\pi$ is the logit link function, and $\Phi$ is as scale parameter (i.e. the cumulative distribution function), for all $i$ countries, and years $t$.} Generalized estimating equations were introduced by \citet{Liang1986} to fit clustered, repeated/correlated, and panel data.\footnote{\citet[322]{Zorn2006}. This method is especially well suited to analyze binary data (\citet{Hanley2003a}), something particularly useful given the nature of the dependent variable. GEE methods require analysts to parameterize the working correlation matrix. While GEE models are robust to misspecification of the correlation structure (\citet[139]{Hedeker2006}), following \citet[166]{Hardin2013}, the ``independence'' working covariance structure was used, since observations were collected over time.} From a substantive standpoint, GEE models provide an estimated marginal mean, or the \emph{weighted average} of all cluster-specific effects (or conditional means). Model 3 is a conditional logit.\footnote{More formally, the next equation was fitted:

\begin{equation}\label{clogit:eq}
\pi_{i,t}=\Phi(\beta_{0} + \beta_{1}\text{log(Industrial Growth)}_{i,t}+\beta_{2}\text{log(Agricultural Growth)}_{i,t}+\beta_{3}\text{log(Total Population)}_{i,t}+\alpha_{i})
\end{equation}
where $\alpha$ are the country fixed effects for all countries $i$.}. Since population has been associated with the probability elites expand the franchise,\footnote{\citet[892-893]{Engerman2005}.} and consequently the tax base, country-year population was included as a control variable. 


