% geographical self-selection
A second potential issue might be whether certain sectors self-select into less earthquake-prone geographical locations. For instance, it might be argued that agricultural areas, being mostly rural, might have lower constructions, while industrial areas, being more urban, might have both highly populated municipalities and higher constructions (edifices), potentially showing higher default death-tolls. To rule-out this possibility, a hierarchical variant of \autoref{model:2} was estimated. Using the same set of control variables, \autoref{model:1} considers whether earthquake magnitudes affect the death-toll of agricultural, industrial or mixed municipalities in different ways.\footnote{More formally, \autoref{model:1} was fitted: 

\begin{equation} \label{model:1}
\begin{split}
\text{Deaths} \;\sim\; & \text{Poisson}(\lambda_{i})\\
log(\lambda_{i})  = 
&\;\mu + 
\beta_{1_j}\text{Magnitude}^2_{i} +
\beta_{2}\text{Latitude}_{i} + 
\beta_{3}\text{Longitude}_{i} + \\
& \beta_{4}\text{Population}_{i} +
\beta_{5}\text{Urban}_{i} + 
\beta_{6_t}\text{Year}_{i}
\end{split}
\end{equation}

where,

\begin{equation*} \label{indexes:1}
\begin{split}
i_{1,...I} & \; \text{and} \; \text{I}=\Sexpr{N} \;  \text{observations},\\
j_{1,...J} & \; \text{and} \; \text{J}=\Sexpr{NSector} \;  \text{sectors},\\
t_{1,...T} & \; \text{and} \; \text{T}=\Sexpr{yearN} \;  \text{years}.
\end{split}
\end{equation*}
} \autoref{sectoral:model:regression:table:run} suggests that death-tolls are orthogonal to the economic sector. Belonging to an agricultural or industrial sector contributes with $\Sexpr{reg.results.table.sectoral[rownames(reg.results.table.sectoral) == "Magnitude [Agr]",1]}$ or $\Sexpr{reg.results.table.sectoral[rownames(reg.results.table.sectoral) == "Magnitude [Ind]",1]}$ additional deaths, respectively.


