% sectoral unity
Finally, it could be argued that the distinction between two separate and opposite sectors is inaccurate. Some historians claim that since landowners also invested in industry,\footnote{\citet[57, 95]{Kirsch:1977aa}, citing \citet[]{Bauer:2008kx}, who explains that ``[m]iners and merchants bought haciendas but landowners in turn invested in banks, insurance companies, commercial firms and the incipient industrial sector.'' \citet[23]{Coatsworth2002} argue that ``[t]he only landowners that mattered in 19th century Latin American politics were those for whom land represented but one asset in a much broader portfolio.''} there was a blurry class division between the industrial and agricultural sectors.\footnote{\citet[30, 44, 94, 108]{Bauer:2008kx}.} Perhaps the most cited reference regarding this issue is \citet[231-247]{Veliz1963}. However, there are a number of stylized facts that strongly suggest that there was indeed a structural sectoral cleavage. For example, it was common that industrialists invested in real estate. Yet, in many instances they did so \emph{just} to obtain credit. \citet[59]{Kirsch:1977aa} explains that ``in a \emph{rural society} land offered one of the best guarantees for loans [since] loans could not be secured by equipment, machinery, or inventory. Only real estate was acceptable collateral.''\footnote{Emphases are mine.} In fact, this practice shows how the credit system was oriented to give unfair advantage to the landed elites.\footnote{\citet[9]{UndaGutierrez2017} explains that in Mexico, industrial elites complied with the income tax in exchange for having a credit system more adequate for them.} Similarly, \citet[174]{Zeitlin:1984aa} finds ``the combined ownership of capital and landed property was a distinctive quality of \emph{certain} [elites] actors,''\footnote{Emphasis is mine.} not \emph{all} elites. There were also other instances where miners invested in banking. Yet, \citet{Segall1953} argues that Chilean bankers, after the crisis of the mining sector around the 1870s, had acquired a number of mineral deposits given as collateral years before. And finally, but for the Argentinean case, \citet[609]{Hora2002} explains that ``the image of an entrepreneurial elite with assets \emph{scattered throughout several spheres of investment} does not appear entirely correct.''\footnote{Emphasis is mine.}


% dual sector model (theory)
Additionally, there are structural reasons to believe that cross-sectoral investments were not efficient. The ``dual sector'' model argues that the economy is divided into agriculture and industry.\footnote{\citet[311]{Jorgenson1961}.} One finding of this paradigm is that the ``natural'' structural role of the agricultural sector is to provide labor and cheap foodstuff to the industrial sector.\footnote{\citet[114]{Ranis:1964uq}. \citet[129]{ReyesCampos2015} documents a real increment in industrial salaries around 1938.} For instance, \citet[326]{Dixit:1973aa} argues that the ``agricultural sector \emph{must} fulfill [...] its dual \emph{role} of supplier of labour to industry and of food for the industrial labour force.''\footnote{Emphases are mine.} The rationale is that more efficient agricultural techniques make agricultural production less labor intensive, allowing landowners to free workers, which the industrial sector can rely on.\footnote{\citet[498]{Johnston1951}.} Surplus of labor naturally leads to a reallocation of redundant workers into the industrial sector, which is the crux of economic development.\footnote{\citet[7]{Ranis:1964uq} and \citet[51]{Leibenstein:1957aa}.} \citet[]{Nurkse:1953aa}, in fact, argues that development means to employ the surplus labor.\footnote{Similarly, \citet[621-622]{Matsuyama1991} points out that  ``[i]ndustrialization [\emph{consists of}] a shift of resources from agriculture to manufacturing.''} % If the agricultural sector lacks economic efficiency, the industrial sector hardly develops, leading to a stagnant economy. As \citet[59]{Kuznets1961a} puts it, ``economic growth is \emph{impossible} unless there is a substantial rise in product per worker in the agricultural sector.''\footnote{Emphasis is mine. \citet[105]{Hayami1969} argue that industrialization is ``\emph{conditioned}'' by agricultural productivity.} 


